    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>

    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none space-y-4 text-gray-700">
      <p>
        Skills Logbook provides a practical, skills-based approach to tracking student progress in Technologies
        education within the Scottish Curriculum for Excellence framework.
      </p>

      <p>
        The system draws inspiration from established competency-based models such as Scouts badges and RYA
        qualifications, emphasizing clear skill demonstration over subjective grading. Students progress through
        bronze, silver, and gold skill levels across curriculum areas, with badges awarded when proficiency
        thresholds are met.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-6 mb-3">Educational Approach</h3>

      <p>
        Rather than focusing on comparative assessment, this system prioritizes <strong>evidence of skill
        demonstration</strong>. Teachers identify relevant skills aligned with project work and mark them as
        demonstrated when students successfully complete activities requiring those competencies.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4 my-6">
        <p class="text-blue-900">
          <strong>Key Principle:</strong> The system tracks that students have successfully demonstrated a skill,
          providing clear evidence of curriculum coverage without requiring subjective quality judgments on
          creative project work.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-6 mb-3">Addressing BGE Tracking Challenges</h3>

      <p>
        This approach emerged from recognizing the need for a more consistent and accessible method of tracking
        BGE progress in Technologies. The logbook format provides clear visibility of curriculum coverage while
        remaining practical for classroom implementation.
      </p>

      <p>
        By organizing skills into topic areas and progressive levels, the system supports both formative
        assessment during projects and summative reporting requirements, while maintaining alignment with
        Experiences and Outcomes.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-6 mb-3">Implementation</h3>

      <p>
        Teachers select appropriate skills at the beginning of a project or unit. As students work, demonstrated
        competencies are marked off. This allows for differentiationâ€”most students may demonstrate bronze-level
        skills during a project, while some may show proficiency at silver or gold levels through extended work
        or exceptional application.
      </p>

      <p>
        When students have demonstrated 75% or more of the skills within a topic area at a particular level,
        they become eligible for the corresponding badge, providing both motivation and clear progression markers.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

